title: A Randomized, Double-blind, Placebo-controlled, Parallel-group Study to Assess the Safety, Tolerability, Pharmacokinetics and Pharmacodynamics of Multiple Oral Doses of CNP520 in Healthy Elderly Subjects
description_brief: The study determined the safety of CNP520 in healthy elderly over 3 months. Data relevant for Pharmacokinetic/Pharmacodynamic modeling were obtained in order to define the target dose in subsequent efficacy studies.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: Participants were randomized in a 1:1:1:1:1 ratio to 5 treatment groups: placebo, CNP520 2 mg, CNP520 10 mg, CNP520 35 mg and CNP520 85 mg.

certainAgreement.otherDetails: The terms and conditions of Novartis' agreements with its investigators may vary. However, Novartis does not prohibit any investigator from publishing. Any publications from a single-site are postponed until the publication of the pooled data (i.e., data from all sites) in the clinical trial or disclosure of trial results in their entirety.

explanation_target: Reason: The investigational product CNP520 is described in the trial as an oral compound given to healthy elderly to assess safety, tolerability, PK/PD and to define target dose for efficacy studies. The goal of measuring CSF Aβ and related pharmacodynamics in early studies indicates the drug is intended to modify Alzheimer’s biology (amyloid production) rather than only treat symptoms. citeturn0search2turn0search0.

Act: Web search identifies CNP520 as umibecestat, a potent, selective small‑molecule BACE1 (β‑secretase) inhibitor developed for lowering Aβ production. The medicinal chemistry and preclinical/early clinical PK/PD papers describe CNP520/umibecestat as a small‑molecule β‑secretase inhibitor that reduced CSF and brain Aβ and was evaluated in Phase 1/2 safety and PD studies. citeturn0search5turn0search4.

Key trial detail supporting classification: The trial title and summary explicitly state multiple oral doses of CNP520 were given to healthy elderly over 3 months to obtain PK/PD data and define target dose for efficacy studies—consistent with a disease‑targeting prevention/development program. citeturn0search2.

Reflect: Given CNP520 is a small molecule whose mechanism is inhibition of BACE1 to reduce amyloid‑β production, it fits the definition of 'disease‑targeted small molecule' (small‑molecule drug targeting Alzheimer’s pathology). For transparency, later larger prevention trials with CNP520 (umibecestat) were discontinued after interim analyses raised safety/efficacy concerns (worsening on some cognitive measures), which does not change the mechanistic classification but is relevant context. citeturn0search6turn0search7.

Web sources used: identification and mechanism (umibecestat / BACE1 inhibitor) — Journal of Medicinal Chemistry / PubMed. citeturn0search5turn0search4; early clinical PK/PD and safety in elderly and the 3‑month Phase 2a description — clinical trial record. citeturn0search2; summary of PD and rationale for prevention studies — EMBO press/EMBO Molecular Medicine. citeturn0search0; later trial discontinuation and safety signal in larger prevention trials — Novartis/press reports and Alzheimer advocacy summaries. citeturn0search7turn0search6.
